# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1882-cleveland-blues-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1882-cleveland-blues-season/1879-cleveland-blues-season] The 1879 season was the National League debut for the **Cleveland Blues**.
[src:1882-cleveland-blues-season/1879-cleveland-blues-season] They finished the season 27–55, sixth in the eight-team National League.
[src:1882-cleveland-blues-season/1880-cleveland-blues-season] The **1880 Cleveland Blues** finished the season at 47–37, good enough for a third-place finish in the National League.
[src:1882-cleveland-blues-season/1881-cleveland-blues-season] The **1881 Cleveland Blues** finished the season at 36–48, seventh place in the National League.
[src:1882-cleveland-blues-season/1882-baltimore-orioles-season] The 19th century's version of the **Baltimore Orioles** were founded in 1882 as part of the new American Association.
[src:1882-cleveland-blues-season/1882-baltimore-orioles-season] Owned by wealthy Harry Von der Horst, the Orioles finished the season in last place with only 19 wins.
[src:1882-cleveland-blues-season/1882-boston-red-caps-season] The **1882 Boston Red Caps season** was the 12th season of the franchise.
[src:1882-cleveland-blues-season/1882-boston-red-caps-season] The Red Caps were a team in transition, as co-founder and longtime manager Harry Wright left the team and was replaced by John Morrill.
[src:1882-cleveland-blues-season/1882-buffalo-bisons-season] The **1882 Buffalo Bisons** finished the season with a 45–39 record, good for third place in the National League.
[src:1882-cleveland-blues-season/1882-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1882 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 11th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the seventh in the National League and the fifth at Lakefront Park.
[src:1882-cleveland-blues-season/1882-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 55–29, 3 games ahead of the second place Providence Grays.
[src:1882-cleveland-blues-season/1882-cleveland-blues-season] The Cleveland Blues finished the 1882 season at 42–40, fifth place in the National League.
